+# CVE-2023-0286 — OpenSSL x400Address Type Confusion (cryptography 36.0.1)
+
+## Summary
+
+CVE-2023-0286 is a type confusion vulnerability in OpenSSL's X.509
+GeneralName handling (`GENERAL_NAME_cmp`). The bug resides entirely in
+OpenSSL's C source (`crypto/x509v3/v3_genn.c` and
+`include/openssl/x509v3.h`) and is not present in the Python
+cryptography package source code.
+
+## Root Cause
+
+OpenSSL incorrectly declared the `x400Address` field in the
+`GENERAL_NAME` union as `ASN1_TYPE *` instead of `ASN1_STRING *`.
+The comparison function `GENERAL_NAME_cmp` then calls `ASN1_TYPE_cmp()`
+on what is actually an `ASN1_STRING *`, producing a type confusion that
+can lead to memory disclosure or denial of service when processing
+malformed X.400 address fields in certificates or CRLs.
+
+The fix changes the field type to `ASN1_STRING *` and updates the caller
+to use `ASN1_STRING_cmp()`.
+Reference commit: https://github.com/openssl/openssl/commit/2f7530077e0ef79d98718138716bc51ca0cad658
+
+## Impact on the cryptography Package
+
+The Python `cryptography` package (v36.0.1) uses CFFI to call OpenSSL
+at runtime via the system libssl/libcrypto. The CFFI binding for
+`GENERAL_NAME` in `src/_cffi_src/openssl/x509v3.py` uses an opaque
+struct layout and does not expose the `x400Address` field — there is no
+Python-level code to patch for this CVE.
+
+The vulnerable code path executes entirely inside the system OpenSSL
+shared library, not within the cryptography package's own source files.
+
+## Remediation
+
+For environments using a system OpenSSL: upgrade to a version that
+includes the fix (>= 1.1.1t or >= 3.0.8).
+
+For environments using a bundled OpenSSL (manylinux wheels): rebuild the
+wheel against a patched OpenSSL release.
+
+## References
+
+- OpenSSL security advisory: https://www.openssl.org/news/secadv/20230207.txt
+- NVD entry: https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2023-0286
-- 
